This is a textbook example of **coverage-padding tests** — every production method is called (→ 95% line coverage) but almost nothing is actually verified. Here's the severity-ranked audit:

---

## 🔴 CRITICAL — No assertion at all (tests can never fail)

These tests execute code but assert nothing. A regression could ship and these would still pass green.

### 1. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)
**Anti-pattern:** Fire-and-forget — no verification the product was persisted.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var saved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(saved);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", saved.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, saved.Price);
```

### 2. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)
**Anti-pattern:** Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price actually changed.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

### 3. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38)
**Anti-pattern:** Removes a product but never verifies it's gone.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

### 4. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)
**Anti-pattern:** Doesn't even capture the return in a variable for assertion. Calls `GetProductCount()` on an empty catalog — tests nothing.
```csharp
// FIX:
Assert.AreEqual(0, _catalog.GetProductCount());
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
```

### 5. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68)
**Anti-pattern:** Applies a 10% discount but never checks any prices changed. A no-op implementation would pass.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
var w = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, w!.Price);   // 9.99 * 0.90
var g = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002");
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, g!.Price);  // 19.99 * 0.90
```

### 6. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 84)
**Anti-pattern:** Imports CSV but never verifies any product was created.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
var p = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
